POP Language Specification v1
Introduction
POP (Prompt-Oriented Programming) is a structured natural-language specification language that compiles into source code.
Rather than directly expressing implementation details in a programming language, POP allows programmers to describe the structure, behavior, constraints, and relationships of a system in human-readable form. A POP compiler generates executable source code from this specification.
POP is designed around the assumption that modern AI systems are capable of producing high-quality implementations when given sufficient structure and guidance. The purpose of POP is not to eliminate interpretation, but to constrain and direct it.
The primary output of a POP document is source code in a target programming language.

───

Core Principles
Explicit Structure, Inferred Implementation
Program structure should be explicit.
Implementation details may be inferred when they do not materially affect correctness or intended behavior.
Stability Over Determinism
POP does not require deterministic compilation.
Instead, POP evaluates and reports the stability of a specification.
Stable specifications should produce materially equivalent implementations across reasonable compilations.
Refusal of Critical Ambiguity
Compilers should avoid making decisions that materially affect correctness, safety, architecture, or observable behavior without sufficient guidance.
Insufficiently specified requirements should generate findings and may be rejected according to compilation policy.
Human Readability First
POP documents are primarily human-readable design artifacts.
Compiler convenience should not take precedence over readability and maintainability.

───

Documents
A POP document consists of paragraphs.
Each paragraph defines exactly one entity.
Except for Actions, paragraph order has no semantic meaning.

───

Entity Model
Entities are the core structural units of POP.
Each entity has a kind.
POP v1 defines five entity kinds:
• Function
• Type
• Import
• Modifier
• Action
Entity kinds should be declared explicitly.

───

Naming
Functions and Types require explicit names.
Entity names must be unique within a document's visible scope.
Documents may not contain multiple visible entities with the same name.
Shadowing is not supported.
Imports do not override local entities.
Local entities do not override imported entities.
Name conflicts must be resolved explicitly.

───

Functions
Functions describe reusable behavior.
Functions may reference other entities by name.
Function specifications should provide enough information to allow reliable implementation.
Example:
[function Register User]
Validate the registration request, hash the password, and store the user record.

───

Types
Types describe the structure and meaning of data.
Types may reference other Types.
The generated representation is target-language dependent.
Example:
[type User]
A registered customer with an email address, password hash, and account status.

───

Imports
Imports expose entities from another POP document.
Imported entities retain their original internal references and context.
References inside imported entities continue to resolve against the imported document.
Imports may expose all entities from a document or a selected subset.

───

Modifiers
Modifiers define document-wide constraints.
Modifiers may influence:
• interpretation
• interfaces
• implementation strategies
• validation requirements
• coding conventions
• architectural constraints
Modifiers may establish assumptions about the target runtime, frameworks, libraries, deployment environment, or other capabilities available during generation.
Modifiers apply to the entire document.
POP v1 does not support scoped modifiers.
Example:
[modifier]
All file operations are asynchronous.
Example:
[modifier]
Use the OpenAI SDK for chat completion requests.

───

Actions
Actions describe executable runtime behavior.
Actions are emitted in document order.
Multiple Actions are allowed.
Actions are not intended to be reusable entities.
Actions do not share implicit local variables or execution context.
Example:
[action]
Start the web server and begin listening for requests.

───

References
References are name-based.
A reference is valid when its intended target can be identified unambiguously by a competent programmer reading the document.
Compilers should resolve references conservatively.
Unclear references should generate findings.

───

External Context
POP entities may reference:
• files
• environment variables
• compiler-provided configuration
• other external artifacts
External artifacts are not POP entities.
POP v1 does not define variables, resources, or asset entities.
The compiler is responsible for validating external references.

───

Stability
Stability is a first-class language concept.
Stability measures how consistently a specification is likely to be interpreted by competent programmers and compliant compilers.
Examples:
Low stability:
"Sort users."
Higher stability:
"Sort users by creation date ascending."
Very high stability:
"Sort users by creation date ascending using merge sort."
Stability is a property of the specification, not of any particular implementation.

───

Findings
Compilers analyze POP documents and produce findings.
Examples include:
• contradictory definitions
• ambiguous references
• missing requirements
• instability risks
• unresolved external references
• architectural concerns
Findings should be descriptive and actionable.
Compilers are encouraged to explain why a finding was generated and suggest improvements.
Findings are not required to be exhaustive.

───

Compilation Policy
Compilation policy determines how findings affect compilation.
Policies may:
• reject
• warn
• note
• ignore
The same POP document may be accepted under one policy and rejected under another.

───

Relationship to AI Software Generation
POP may be used alongside AI-assisted software generation systems.
POP provides a human-readable and reviewable representation of software structure and intent.
AI systems may generate POP documents, refine POP documents, or compile POP documents into code.
Because POP documents are plain-text specifications, they integrate naturally with version control, code review, and peer review workflows. Changes can be reviewed at the specification level before generated code is inspected.
POP does not prescribe any particular software development workflow.

───

Appendix A - Examples
Hello World
[action]
Display "Hello World".

───

User Greeting
[type User]
A user with a name.
[function Greet User]
Display "Hello" followed by the user's name.
[action]
Create a user named World and Greet User.

───

Function Composition
[function Validate User]
Ensure the user has a non-empty name and a valid email address.
[function Register User]
Validate User and store the user in the database.
This example demonstrates how Functions may reference other Functions by name.

───

Explicitly Deferred
The following topics are intentionally outside the scope of POP v1:
• private entities
• entity aliases
• scoped modifiers
• resource entities
• variables
• deterministic compilation guarantees
• stability scoring systems
• compiler interoperability standards
• formal verification
• optimization directives
These may be introduced in future revisions.
